Apache Solr is a web application which is built on lucene API librabries. 
Extending and overriding some of its features 
It offers REST ful APIs(XML,JSON,CSV,binary and HTTP) for easy interactions 
Initially it is designed for limited data set 
Now the newer version is re-architected for huge big data sets, which includes terabytes to petabytes 
Solr provides advanced full-text search capabilities, web-scale dynamic and elastic scaling and anadministratic application for easy configuration and management. 
It simplifies the development pf search applicatioin. 
The Apache Solr is includes Request handlers for incoming requestr and request writers/update handlers for updating the index
Solr instances and core can host multiple "cores and indexes". which is analogeous to datasets

Real Time Example:

If your data is stored in a normal database, searching text quickly and intelligently is hard and slow.
Apache Solr is like a super-powered search engine you attach to your data.
It is built on top of Apache Lucene, which is a low-level text search library.
Think of it like this:
Lucene = the engine inside the car
Solr = the full car (engine + steering + dashboard + controls)

How Solr Works:

We Give Documents in JSON/XML format.
(JSON)
{
  "id": "1",
  "name": "Red Running Shoes",
  "price": 80,
  "category": "shoes"
}

Solr:
*Breaks text into tokens
*Stores them in an inverted index
*Makes it searchable

How We Search: (Querying)

*we send a request like:
http://localhost:8983/solr/products/select?q=red+shoes

Solr:
*Looks into its index
*Finds matching documents
*Scores them by relevance
*Returns results in JSON

How to Access Solr UI:

*open browser using: http://localhost:8983
*You’ll see the Solr Admin UI Dashboard.
*That is Solr’s control panel.

What Can we Access Inside the UI?
🔹 Dashboard:

*JVM memory
*System info
*Solr version
*Core count
(This is your health monitor).

🔹 Core Admin (Standalone Mode)

*Create core
*Reload core
*Delete core
*Swap core
(Think core as one search Database) 

🔹 Collections (SolrCloud Mode)

*Collections
*Shards
*Replicas
(This is distributed Solr).

